 <p>After we more fully analyze vector functions, we will examine scalar functions that have multiple input variables. These&nbsp;<em>multivariate&nbsp;</em>(or <em>multivariable</em>) functions are fundamental to conceptualizing the complexities of the world around us. We again will extend our vast experience with single-variable scalar functions to account for more complex relationships between variables.&nbsp;</p>
        <p>Recall that we have previously defined functions specifically as the relationships between two variables that have an input-output (or a dependent-independent) relationship. If a set of points <img class="equation_image" title="(x,y)" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/(x%252Cy)?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: (x,y)" data-equation-content="(x,y)" data-ignore-a11y-check="" /> define the graph of a function&nbsp;<img class="equation_image" title="y=f(x)" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/y%253Df(x)?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: y=f(x)" data-equation-content="y=f(x)" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />, what we mean is that at each <img class="equation_image" title="x" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/x?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: x" data-equation-content="x" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />-value we have a&nbsp;<strong>single&nbsp;</strong>assigned <img class="equation_image" title="y" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/y?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: y" data-equation-content="y" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />-value (Note that any <img class="equation_image" title="y" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/y?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: y" data-equation-content="y" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />-value can have multiple <img class="equation_image" title="x" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/x?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: x" data-equation-content="x" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />-values associated with it). We say that <img class="equation_image" title="x" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/x?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: x" data-equation-content="x" data-ignore-a11y-check="" /> is the input of the function and <img class="equation_image" title="y" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/y?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: y" data-equation-content="y" data-ignore-a11y-check="" /> is the output of the function, and together, the graph comprises the points <img class="equation_image" title="(x,y)=(x,f(x))" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/(x%252Cy)%253D(x%252Cf(x))?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: (x,y)=(x,f(x))" data-equation-content="(x,y)=(x,f(x))" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />. In this way, <img class="equation_image" title="y" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/y?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: y" data-equation-content="y" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />&nbsp;<em><strong>depends</strong></em><strong>&nbsp;</strong>on <img class="equation_image" title="x" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/x?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: x" data-equation-content="x" data-ignore-a11y-check="" /> because you can alter the <img class="equation_image" title="y" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/y?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: y" data-equation-content="y" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />-value specifically by altering the <img class="equation_image" title="x" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/x?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: x" data-equation-content="x" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />-value. This is depicted in the following GeoGebra application.&nbsp;</p>
        <p>You may alter the "x=" slider to view the different points on the graph of <img class="equation_image" title="f(x)=\sin(x)+\frac{x}{5}" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/f(x)%253D%255Csin(x)%252B%255Cfrac%257Bx%257D%257B5%257D?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: f(x)=\sin(x)+\frac{x}{5}" data-equation-content="f(x)=\sin(x)+\frac{x}{5}" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />. The input <img class="equation_image" title="x" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/x?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: x" data-equation-content="x" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />&nbsp;gives the horizontal component of the point <img class="equation_image" title="(x,y)" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/(x%252Cy)?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: (x,y)" data-equation-content="(x,y)" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />, and the output <img class="equation_image" title="f(x)" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/f(x)?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: f(x)" data-equation-content="f(x)" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />&nbsp;gives the vertical component of the point <img class="equation_image" title="(x,y)" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/(x%252Cy)?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: (x,y)" data-equation-content="(x,y)" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />. Notice that we primarily change <img class="equation_image" title="y" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/y?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: y" data-equation-content="y" data-ignore-a11y-check="" /> by first sliding <img class="equation_image" title="x" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/x?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: x" data-equation-content="x" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />.</p>
        <p><iframe style="border: 0px;" title="243 Mod 4 Single Var Function" src="https://www.geogebra.org/material/iframe/id/mvpqg764/width/739/height/456/border/888888/sfsb/true/smb/false/stb/false/stbh/false/ai/false/asb/false/sri/false/rc/false/ld/false/sdz/false/ctl/false" width="739px" height="456px" loading="lazy" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></p>
        <p>We can similarly define <img class="equation_image" title="(x,y)" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/(x%252Cy)?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: (x,y)" data-equation-content="(x,y)" data-ignore-a11y-check="" /> on the graph of a function with <img class="equation_image" title="y" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/y?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: y" data-equation-content="y" data-ignore-a11y-check="" /> as its input so that the curve is defined by the points <img class="equation_image" title="(f(y),y)" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/(f(y)%252Cy)?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: (f(y),y)" data-equation-content="(f(y),y)" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />, but this is less common.&nbsp;</p>
        <p>Now, we will create a relationship between three or more variables and require that one variable&nbsp;<em>depends on&nbsp;</em>the other variables, thus making a function again in the same way that we defined single-variable functions.</p>
        <p>A classic visualization of this is to define the points <img class="equation_image" title="(x,y,z)" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/(x%252Cy%252Cz)?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: (x,y,z)" data-equation-content="(x,y,z)" data-ignore-a11y-check="" /> on a surface as a function <img class="equation_image" title="f" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/f?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: f" data-equation-content="f" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />&nbsp;of two input variables, <img class="equation_image" title="x" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/x?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: x" data-equation-content="x" data-ignore-a11y-check="" /> and <img class="equation_image" title="y" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/y?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: y" data-equation-content="y" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />. Here, we can freely change both <img class="equation_image" title="x" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/x?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: x" data-equation-content="x" data-ignore-a11y-check="" /> and <img class="equation_image" title="y" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/y?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: y" data-equation-content="y" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />, and for each possible pair <img class="equation_image" title="(x,y)" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/(x%252Cy)?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: (x,y)" data-equation-content="(x,y)" data-ignore-a11y-check="" /> we get a&nbsp;<em><strong>single</strong> <img class="equation_image" title="z" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/z?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: z" data-equation-content="z" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />-</em>value, <img class="equation_image" title="z=f(x,y)" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/z%253Df(x%252Cy)?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: z=f(x,y)" data-equation-content="z=f(x,y)" data-ignore-a11y-check="" /> (again, any one <em><img class="equation_image" title="z" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/z?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: z" data-equation-content="z" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />-</em>value might be associated with multiple <img class="equation_image" title="(x,y)" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/(x%252Cy)?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: (x,y)" data-equation-content="(x,y)" data-ignore-a11y-check="" /> pairs). Typically, like before with single variable functions, the values of the function <img class="equation_image" title="f" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/f?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: f" data-equation-content="f" data-ignore-a11y-check="" /> can be visually interpreted as a height (hence, <img class="equation_image" title="z" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/z?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: z" data-equation-content="z" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />) defined at any point on the <img class="equation_image" title="x-y" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/x-y?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: x-y" data-equation-content="x-y" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />&nbsp;plane.</p>
        <p>This is depicted in the following GeoGebra application. The left screen simulates the <img class="equation_image" title="x-y" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/x-y?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: x-y" data-equation-content="x-y" data-ignore-a11y-check="" /> plane, and the right screen gives a surface defined as the graph of a function <img class="equation_image" title="f(x,y)" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/f(x%252Cy)?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: f(x,y)" data-equation-content="f(x,y)" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />. You may click and drag the point <img class="equation_image" title="(x,y)" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/(x%252Cy)?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: (x,y)" data-equation-content="(x,y)" data-ignore-a11y-check="" /> either on the left screen or on the <img class="equation_image" title="x-y" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/x-y?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: x-y" data-equation-content="x-y" data-ignore-a11y-check="" /> plane on the right screen. You may also click and drag either screen and scroll to zoom in and out to alter your perspective. You may select the "Reset 3D Zoom" button to return to a global look at the function.&nbsp;</p>
        <p><iframe style="border: 0px;" title="243 Mod 4 Multivariable Function" src="https://www.geogebra.org/material/iframe/id/krfy4jsw/width/751/height/652/border/888888/sfsb/true/smb/false/stb/false/stbh/false/ai/false/asb/false/sri/false/rc/false/ld/false/sdz/true/ctl/false" width="751px" height="652px" loading="lazy" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></p>
        <p>Notice that just as in the single-variable case, we have a dependent-independent relationship between the variables that make up the surface. The primary difference is that we now have two separate variables, <img class="equation_image" title="x" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/x?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: x" data-equation-content="x" data-ignore-a11y-check="" /> and <img class="equation_image" title="y" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/y?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: y" data-equation-content="y" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />, that both can be altered to change the value of <img class="equation_image" title="z=f(x,y)" src="https://erau.instructure.com/equation_images/z%253Df(x%252Cy)?scale=1" alt="LaTeX: z=f(x,y)" data-equation-content="z=f(x,y)" data-ignore-a11y-check="" />.</p>
        <p>This forms the foundation of the rest of the course, and we will be thoroughly exploring the properties of multivariable functions as we continue on in the remaining modules.</p>